ir bankruptcies. For many middle-class Americans, the findings show, financial stability is fragile-almost any setback can be disastrous. The erosion of job stability, divorce and family instability, the visible and invisible costs of medical care, the burden of home ownership, and the staggering weight of consumer debt financed with plastic combine to threaten the financial security of growing numbers of middle-class families. The authors view the bankruptcy process in the light of changing cultural and economic factors and consider what this may signify for the future of a large, secure, and dynamic middle class.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBankruptcyxUnited States. 0aBankruptcyzUnited States. 0aConsumer creditxUnited States. 0aConsumer creditzUnited States. 0aCrédit à la consommationxÉtats-Unis. 0aFaillitexÉtats-Unis. 0aFinance, PersonalxUnited States. 0aFinance, PersonalzUnited States. 0aFinances personnellesxÉtats-UnisxUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aWarren, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWestbrook, Jay Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300128147423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300128147.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles